post_text:
Birthday treat update:

For all those who have a child who wants to give treats out to their class for their birthday. We have recently been given permission to allow birthday treats under the following parameters:

-Treats must be store bought
-Must be in a sealed box
-Must be individually wrapped

Parents can bring the classroom treats to the front office and office staff can ensure they are taken to the child’s classroom. According to our current health guidance we are not yet able to have parents past the front office, but we look forward to when we can do so. Treat handout will be handled in a sanitary way with clean surfaces and hands.
Thanks so much!

post_text: AES Update: Teacher letters for registered students/smart start.
text: AES Update: Teacher letters for registered students/smart start.

post_text:
Dear Parents,
What a whirlwind of a summer this has been!!! We are looking forward with anticipation to a new school year that will be something never experienced before. We are anxious to get your students back in the schools. Thank you for those of you who have already registered your student(s).

If you have not yet registered your student(s) for school we would ask a huge favor of you to try and get that accomplished by Wednesday, August 5. We are in the midst of trying to build classroom lists and transportation routes. We need to be as accurate on our student count as possible to ensure we have adequate staffing.

To register your student please go to http://www.lcsd2.org/registration.

If you have any questions, please feel free to contact the School District Administration Office 307-885-3811.

Regards,

Lincoln County School District #2

We hope this message finds you all safe and well. Here’s some important information as we look to finish the school year.

Teachers have packaged your child’s personal belongings and will have them ready for you to pick up on the days and times below. We ask that you stay in your cars, tell us your child’s name, and we’ll bring the personal items to you. We’ll have them by the student pick-up/drop-off lane near the school entrance––like we’ve done for packet pick-ups.

TH May 21st–––12:00-6:00
T-TH May 26-28 –––8:00-2:00

We will take library books and lunch money if you have them. Later this week, we will have a new book drop-off box near the entrance of the school where you can drop books at your convenience.

We ask that you return any iPads, if you have one, unless you have made other arrangements with your child’s teacher.

We sincerely appreciate your support during a very trying spring. If you have questions, please contact us at 307-885-8002. #all4afton

post_text: As of right now school will continue in LCSD#2 as planned. Supt. Erickson has a conference call scheduled at 8:30 a.m. on Monday morning with Governor Gordon, Jillian Balow and Dr. Alexia Harrist. Following the call the district administration team will meet to discuss recommendations based on that conference call. We encourage parents to do what they feel is best for their own family. Leniency with absences will be handled on a case by case basis. Updates will be provided on social media and school websites as they become available. If more urgent communication is needed the school district will use the emergency school notification system. A message will be sent out later this afternoon to all households containing the same information as this post.

post_text: (Mr. NIelsen shared some artwork with us this week. Here are his thoughts about it.) This is one of my favorite units for 2nd grade! Amy Ringholz is a contemporary artist and her work can be found in Jackson Hole, Wyoming! She loves to draw and paint animals. Her focus is always the eye of the animal. Her art is unique in the way she draws and paints shapes on animals. Her use of color is also very beautiful. Students are using colored pencils and have learned how to blend them to create very “yummy” looking colors. I have included some of my “demos” along with students currently in progress with their project. Enjoy!

post_text:
To our veterans: Afton Elementary stands by you. Words cannot express our gratitude for the work and sacrifice you do and have done for our country.

This video was shown today during our special Veteran's Day assembly. As the chorus was sung, the students-without any prompting from the adults-began singing along. There weren't many dry eyes as the students boldly sang the words: "God Bless the USA!"

We dedicate this video to the Wyoming National Guard Charlie Company, 1st Battalion, 297th Infantry Regiment who are currently deployed overseas. We love and miss you! (Make sure to watch all the way to the end!)

Special thanks to Case Tippetts for lending his beautiful voice to the song. Also thank you to SVI Media for the video and audio recording and editing.

#GodBlesstheUSA

It's looking like it will be too cold to do our Halloween parade outdoors, so we're going to parade indoors tomorrow. Parade will start at 12:45. The best place for you to observe will be along the wall of the main hallway. We will parade along the main hallway, come to the gym, and make a loop there too before students return to their pods. You're welcome to line the walls of the gym too if you like.

It's fine if students wear their costumes, but we will have time after lunch for them to get dressed if they want to bring it and not wear it all day. Face paint is ok. We ask that students not wear masks until the parade time if a mask is part of their costume. Please no toy weapons! Thanks!

post_text: To begin our school year, each student participated in a collaborative art project. We were artists inspired by Elizabeth (Libs) Elliot. She is a contemporary artist and loves to make quilts. As part of her creative process, she uses a computer program to come up with the design. She inputs the colors and the program spits out the image using basic shapes: squares and triangles. The program has over a million variations and decides the pattern for her. She loves not knowing what the computer will come up with next. We made a paper quilt and the students became the computer and I just gave them the colors to use. We had a great time and it turned out great! Mr. Nielsen

Literacy Week March 4th-7th
Please join us in celebrating Dr. Seuss’ Birthday all week!

Literacy week at Afton Elementary is here and we’re excited to celebrate our love of reading! We’re going to celebrate Dr. Seuss each day by dressing in Seuss style. Please see our schedule below.

Monday: “Cat in the Hat” – Wear a Cat in the Hat or Crazy or Favorite Hat!

Tuesday: “Fox in Socks” – Wear crazy or mismatched socks!

Wednesday: “Wacky Wednesday” – Wear your wackiest, tackiest, mismatch-iest brightly patterned outfit!

Thursday: “Oh the Places You’ll Go” – Wear a shirt from somewhere you’ve been, or want to go! Or you can wear your school spirit shirt!

post_text: Mr. Nielsen teaches our students the styles of a number of great artists. Amy Ringholz is a contemporary artist and her work can be found in Jackson Hole, Wyoming! She loves to draw and paint animals. Her focus is always the eye of the animal. Her art is unique in the way she draws and paints shapes on animals. Her use of color is also very beautiful. Enjoy how well our 2nd graders have portrayed the emotion and feeling coming from the eyes of their colored animals. So fun!

His most famous work is “Starry Night.” Students drew and painted a Star Valley “Starry Night.”
